  Look at Prohibition.  One could argue that that law was influenced by the religion, while others could say it was a backlash against the rampant craziness of the 1920's. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ammelen>Ammelen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I Live Here</span><br>  Posts: 1839<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/18/03 5:29 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=176.topic&index=43>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Ten Commandments Judge</span><hr size=1> There are fundamental differences.<br>
<br>
Theft or murder deprives another human being of his/her basic rights.  It fundamentally affects another person besides the parties that choose to engage in the practice.  Sodomy does not.  Alcohol is somewhat more debatable as you can argue that it causes harm through drunk driving etc.<br>
<br>
Why should I care if two consenting adults want to sodomize each other in the privacy of their own bedroom?  It has no effect on me at all whatsoever.  Let them do what they want.<br>
<br>
There is a utilitarian ethical argument against murder and theft that is not valid against sodomy.<br>
<br>
