<br>
However, the ten commandments residing in a court of law is exponentially more symoblic than a general reference to christianity in a painting.  The ten commandments are basically the rules which govern Christianity and result in the criteria for which man is judged by his maker, and them residing in a place that ultimately judges man gives the impression that the establishment is biased towards the rules displayed in their foyer.<br>
<br>
That courthouse may be 100% unbiased regarding Christianity, but it doesn't matter.  The image they portray gives alot of potential towards the thought of bias, and that's the last thing you want in a court of law.  Unfortunately, image counts here. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ammelen>Ammelen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I Live Here</span><br>  Posts: 1899<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/23/03 8:01 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=176.topic&index=54>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ...</span><hr size=1> I just don't buy it.  I think people are being very oversensitive.  I've never accepted that freedom of religion is the same as freedom from religion.  Rather, I think society should allow many religions to exist and flourish and not try to remove every semblance of them from our society.<br>
<br>
That being said, the state shouldn't practice any particular religion or try to enforce religious law.<br>
<br>
To ignore the influence of religions on our culture is to deny the obvious.  To place the ten commandments there does recognize their historical and cultural importance in our country.  It does not however make them the law of the land.<br>
<br>
I do think the reasoning of this judge is wrong.  He is essentially trying to put Christianity in the courtroom, and he has a long history of doing that.  Thus, I don't agree with his motivations or his arguments.  However, I do think that the anti-religion people are overzealous and need to chill out and not be so damned sensitive.  Our culture is full of references to ideas and beliefs that we may not agree with, but our culture is a melange of those philosophies, and it's ok to recognize that.<br>
